    "summary": "The Kargil War of May to July 1999 was an armed conflict between India and Pakistan in the Kargil district of the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir, fought along some of the world's most inhospitable high-altitude terrain. Pakistani soldiers and Kashmiri militants infiltrated positions on the Indian side of the Line of Control — the de facto border established after the 1971 war — occupying strategic heights that overlooked a vital supply road. India launched Operation Vijay to recapture these positions.\n\nThe conflict was alarming to the international community because both India and Pakistan had tested nuclear weapons in 1998, making this a confrontation between two nuclear-armed states. Under intense US pressure, Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif ordered withdrawal of Pakistani forces in July 1999, with India retaking most of the occupied positions. The war cost approximately 500 Indian and between 400 and 4,000 Pakistani lives. In Pakistan, the withdrawal was deeply unpopular and contributed to the military coup by General Pervez Musharraf in October 1999 that overthrew Sharif. The conflict underscored the dangerous instability of the [[event:2751|India-Pakistan dispute]] over Kashmir.",
